headline.main: ALARIC; OR, THE TYRANT'S VAULT.; A SICILIAN STORY OF EARLY TIMES.

docs.lead_paragraph: CHAPTER I. ALARIC. Not far from the city of Syracuse, when it was the metropolis of all Sicily, an object of longing to ambitious conquerers,and one of the finest cities in the world; not far from this place, upon the shore of the sea, stood a man who had just landed from a vessel that was now sailing away towards the North.

headline.main: PHYSICAL GEOGRAPHY OF NORTH AMERICA.; NUMBER SIX. The Cordillera of the Sierra Madre.

docs.lead_paragraph: This is an immense department of our country of primary significance and interest. Vaguely de nominated as the "Story or Rocky Mo??tains," occupying an inhospitable waste beyond the energies of social adventure, mankind has ??tofore heard the name with indifference, and all minute details with dogmatic aversion. To establish its title to esteem in the popular opinion of the world, the complete reverse of this, is my object.

docs.lead_paragraph: The position of Principal of the Philadelphia Central High School has been resigned by Professor John S. Hart. after an occupancy extending over 16 years. Dr. Hart was chosen upon the resignation of Dr. A. D. Bache, when the latter accepted the charge of the Coast Survey. His administration has been eminently successful.

docs.lead_paragraph: THE CITY MORTALITY.--The health of the City is remarkably good. The deaths reported to the City Inspector last week numbered 348, which is less by 12 than the week preceding, and 53 less than for the corresponding week of last year. There is no epidemic in the City, and of contagious or infectious diseases less than usual.

headline.main: HAVANA.; Arrival of the Empire City.

docs.lead_paragraph: The United States mail steamship Empire City, S. P. CRIFFIN, Esq., commanding, which left NewOrleans at noon of the 20th October, arrived at NewYork yesterday morning. The Empire City arrived at Havana at sunrise of the 26th, having been detained three days on the bar at the Southwest Pass. She left at 5 P. M. of the 26th, and has experienced strong southeasterly winds during the whole passage.
